{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 4.2 PID Implementation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 struct PIDController \{\line
    int256 kp;          // Proportional gain\line
    int256 ki;          // Integral gain\line
    int256 kd;          // Derivative gain\line
    int256 integral;    // Accumulated error\line
    int256 lastError;   // Previous error for derivative\line
    uint256 lastUpdate; // Timestamp of last adjustment\line
    int256 outputMin;   // Minimum allowed output\line
    int256 outputMax;   // Maximum allowed output\line
\}\line
\line
function adjustParameter(PIDController storage pid, int256 measured, int256 target) internal returns (int256) \{\line
    int256 error = target - measured;\line
    int256 dt = int256(block.timestamp - pid.lastUpdate);\line
\line
    pid.integral += error * dt;\line
    int256 derivative = dt > 0 ? (error - pid.lastError) / dt : int256(0);\line
\line
    int256 output = pid.kp * error + pid.ki * pid.integral + pid.kd * derivative;\line
    output = clamp(output, pid.outputMin, pid.outputMax);\line
\line
    pid.lastError = error;\line
    pid.lastUpdate = block.timestamp;\line
\line
    return output;\line
\}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 4.3 Automated Dispute Resolution\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As governance loses dispute resolution authority, the {\f1 DecentralizedTribunal.sol} transitions to fully automated adjudication:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab {\b Schelling point voting}: Random token holder jury selected via VRF\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab {\b Stake-weighted consensus}: Jurors stake to participate, slashed for minority vote\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab {\b Precedent accumulation}: Past rulings create case law that automated system references\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab {\b Appeal reduction}: Each appeal requires 2x the stake, converging to finality\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 After Year 6, the tribunal operates without governance oversight. Disputes are resolved by economic incentives alone.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 5. The Sunset Clause\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 5.1 Mechanism\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 At a predetermined block height (estimated Year 8-10 from genesis), the governance module executes its final action:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1 function executeSunset() external \{\line
    require(block.number >= SUNSET_BLOCK, "Sunset not reached");\line
    require(!sunsetExecuted, "Already sunset");\line
\line
    sunsetExecuted = true;\line
\line
    // Disable all governance functions\line
    governanceEnabled = false;\line
\line
    // Transfer any remaining governance treasury to Shapley pool\line
    uint256 balance = address(this).balance;\line
    if (balance > 0) \{\line
        shapleyDistributor.deposit\{value: balance\}();\line
    \}\line
\line
    // Emit final event\line
    emit GovernanceSunset(block.number, block.timestamp);\line
\}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 5.2 Extension Mechanism\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The sunset can be delayed ONE time by a supermajority vote: - Requires 90% of total (decayed) voting power - Extends sunset by exactly one half-life period - The extension itself has a sunset - A second extension requires 95% supermajority (practically impossible with decayed weights)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This ensures that if something genuinely unexpected happens (e.g., a critical vulnerability discovered at Year 7), there is an escape hatch. But the escape hatch is designed to be almost impossible to use \u8212- which is the point.\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 6. Fork Escape Valve\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 6.1 The Ultimate Safety Net\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If governance becomes corrupt before it decays (e.g., a whale accumulates enough tokens to pass malicious proposals during the Bootstrap phase), users have a nuclear option: {\b fork with zero penalty.}\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The Fractal Fork Network ensures that: 1. Any user can fork the protocol permissionlessly 2. The fork inherits all code and parameters 3. Fee routing to the corrupt parent can be set to 0% (emergency fork exception) 4. Users migrate their liquidity to the clean fork 5. The corrupt parent starves as users leave\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel2 \b \fs28 6.2 Governance Corruption Detection\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Automated monitoring detects governance capture: - Single address controlling >30% of voting power \u8594 ? alert - Proposal passing with <10% voter participation \u8594 ? alert - Proposal that modifies core invariants (fee routing, Shapley, decay) \u8594 ? auto-reject + alert - Flash loan governance detection (voting power spike within 1 block) \u8594 ? auto-reject\par}
{\pard \qc \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\emdash\par}
